  "prompt": "What is a good website for free books?",
  "response": "There are several reputable websites where you can find free books, particularly classic literature and works that are in the public domain. Here are a few popular options:\n\n1. **Project Gutenberg** - This site offers over 60,000 free ebooks, including classic literature and historical texts. You can find works by authors like Jane Austen, Mark Twain, and Charles Dickens.\n\n   Website: [www.gutenberg.org](http://www.gutenberg.org)\n\n2. **Internet Archive** - A digital library that provides free access to millions of books, movies, music, and more. You can borrow or download a wide range of texts.\n\n   Website: [www.archive.org](https://archive.org)\n\n3. **Open Library** - A part of the Internet Archive, Open Library aims to create a web page for every book ever published. It offers millions of free books, especially older works.\n\n   Website: [www.openlibrary.org](https://openlibrary.org)\n\n4. **Google Books** - Google Books has a large collection of free books, especially those that are in the public domain. You can search for specific titles or authors.\n\n   Website: [books.google.com](https://books.google.com)\n\n5. **ManyBooks** - This site offers a large selection of free ebooks, especially classics and indie titles. You can browse by genre and discover new authors.\n\n   Website: [www.manybooks.net](https://www.manybooks.net)\n\n6. **LibriVox** - While primarily an audiobook site, LibriVox offers free audiobooks of public domain texts, read by volunteers. This is a great option if you enjoy listening to books.\n\n   Website: [www.librivox.org](https://librivox.org)\n\nThese sites provide a wealth of reading materials at no cost, ensuring that you can find something that suits your interests!",
